Project 1 — Predict Patient Readmission Risk (Supervised Learning)
Goal: Use patient encounter or hospital data to predict whether a patient will be readmitted within 30 days. (Use Orange Software), Healthcare Analytics
Software: Orange

Example Question : Can we predict whether a patient will be readmitted based on demographics, diagnosis, utilization, LOS, and discharge characteristics?

Possible Dataset Sources
  Diabetes 130-US hospitals dataset (very common for readmission projects) - https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/296/diabetes+130-us+hospitals+for+years+1999-2008
  Any de-identified hospital/claims-like CSV
  Public readmission datasets from Kaggle/UCI - https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/dubradave/hospital-readmissions
  CMS Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program - https://data.cms.gov/provider-data/dataset/9n3s-kdb3

Target Variable/ Data Fields 
  Readmitted → Yes / No

Features You Might Use
  age
  gender
  length of stay
  number of medications
  number of diagnoses
  prior inpatient visits
  emergency visits
  primary diagnosis category
  discharge disposition
  A1C result / lab abnormality flags if available


Orange Workflow.
Widgets to Use
  File
  Data Table
  Select Columns
  Edit Domain (optional)
  Impute
  Continuize
  Rank
  Logistic Regression
  Tree
  Random Forest
  Test & Score
  Confusion Matrix
  ROC Analysis
  Predictions
  Feature Importance or Nomogram if available


Step-by-Step Instructions

Step 1: Import the Data
  Drag File onto the canvas.
  Load your CSV dataset.
  Connect File → Data Table to inspect the data.
  Check: Is the target column present?, Are missing values obvious?, Are categorical columns properly recognized?

Step 2: Set the Target and Clean the Data
  Add Select Columns.
  Move your outcome variable (readmitted) into Target.
  Move ID columns (patient ID, encounter ID) to Meta so they don’t influence the model.
  Keep predictive variables in Features.
  
  Then add:
  Impute → fills missing values
  Continuize → converts categorical variables to numeric format for algorithms like logistic regression

Recommended flow:
  File → Select Columns → Impute → Continuize

Step 3: Explore Which Features Matter
  Add Rank after preprocessing.
  Use information gain / Gini / ANOVA ranking to see which variables are most predictive.

Note the top features:
  prior admissions
  LOS
  number of medications
  diagnosis category
  discharge disposition

This helps you explain the business/clinical interpretation.

Step 4: Train Multiple Models

Add 3 learner widgets:

  Logistic Regression
  Tree
  Random Forest

  Connect them to the preprocessed data pipeline.

Example structure:

  Continuize → Logistic Regression
  Continuize → Tree
  Continuize → Random Forest

Step 5: Evaluate Models

Add Test & Score and connect:

preprocessed data to Test & Score
all 3 models to Test & Score

Inside Test & Score:

Choose Cross Validation
Set folds to 10

Metrics to compare:

  AUC
  CA (classification accuracy)
  F1
  Precision
  Recall

Step 6: Review Errors and ROC

From Test & Score, connect to:

  Confusion Matrix
  ROC Analysis
  What to look at

Confusion Matrix

  True positives = correctly predicted readmissions
  False negatives = missed readmissions → often the most important in healthcare

ROC Curve

  Compare the curves for Logistic Regression vs Tree vs Random Forest
  Higher AUC generally means better separation

Step 7: Interpret the Best Model

If Random Forest performs best:

note that it captured non-linear relationships and interactions

If Logistic Regression performs similarly:

note that it may be easier to explain operationally
